\chapter{Theoretical Background}
\label{chap:theory}

This chapter gives a brief introduction to the Standard Model, models
beyond the Standard Model relevant to this thesis, and the physics of
proton collisions.

\section{The Standard Model}

The Standard Model (SM) of particle physics is the most widely
accepted theory for predicting the interactions of elementary
particles.
It describes all known fundamental particles and the strong and
electroweak forces.

\subsection{Particles and interactions}
Particles in the SM are split into two categories: fermions with
half-integer spin and bosons with integer spin.
The fermions are further divided into those that have color and
interact via the strong force (quarks), and those that do not
(leptons).
There are three generations of both quarks and leptons which are
generally grouped in order of increasing mass.
This is shown in Table~\ref{chap:theory:tab:smfermions}.
Quarks have non-integer charge and are grouped into ``up-type'' ($u$,
$c$, $t$, with charge $+2/3$) and ``down-type'' ($d$, $s$, $b$, with
charge $-1/3$) varieties.
Leptons are grouped by their charges: electrons ($e$), muons
($\mu$), and tau leptons ($\tau$) carry negative charge, and there is
a corresponding chargeless neutrino ($\nu_\ell$) for each charged
lepton.
Antiparticles have identical masses but opposite charges.
The fermion type is sometimes referred to as its flavor.

\begin{table}[]
\centering
\caption{The Standard Model fermions.}
\label{chap:theory:tab:smfermions}
\begin{tabular}{|l | c | c | c|}
\hline
\hline
\multirow{2}{*}{Quarks} & $u^{+2/3}$ & $c^{+2/3}$ & $t^{+2/3}$ \\
                        & $d^{-1/3}$ & $s^{-1/3}$ & $b^{-1/3}$ \\
\hline
\multirow{2}{*}{Leptons} & $e^-$ & $\mu^-$ & $\tau^-$ \\
                         & $\nu_e$ & $\nu_\mu$ & $\nu_\tau$ \\
\hline
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

There are four vector bosons in the Standard Model which mediate
interactions between particles.
Gluons ($g$) interact with quarks and other gluons through the strong
force described by quantum chromodynamics (QCD); they are massless.
Photons ($\gamma$) and the massive weak bosons ($W^\pm$, $Z$) mediate
the electroweak interaction, a unification of the electromagnetic
and weak theories by Glashow, Salam, and Weinberg~\cite{bib:glashow,
bib:weinberg, bib:salam}.
The $W$ and $Z$ bosons interact with all fermion flavors and each
other.
Photons are massless and only couple the charged fermions and the $W$
boson.

